WEBVTT

00:04.871 --> 00:05.839 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Good evening.

00:05.872 --> 00:06.840 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm Judy Woodruff.

00:06.873 --> 00:08.575 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
On the "NewsHour" tonight:

00:08.608 --> 00:10.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
REX TILLERSON, U.S. Secretary of
State: The
current state of U.S.-Russia
relations is

00:10.610 --> 00:12.445 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
at a low point.

00:12.479 --> 00:16.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Secretary of
State Rex Tillerson
and his Russian counterpart meet
to discuss

00:16.716 --> 00:22.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the future of the two countries'
relationship,
amid disagreements over Syria's
use of chemical

00:22.622 --> 00:24.457 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
weapons.

00:24.491 --> 00:28.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then, we sit down with NATO's
secretary-general
after his meeting at the White
House with

00:28.728 --> 00:33.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
President Trump, who has
strongly criticized
the NATO alliance.

00:33.066 --> 00:39.639 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the Trump administration
sets its sights
on space -- how one congressman
who controls

00:39.672 --> 00:44.044 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NASA's purse strings is pushing
to go to the
moon, Mars and beyond.

00:44.077 --> 00:45.912 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

00:45.945 --> 00:48.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN CULBERSON (R), Texas: I
have always wanted
to restore NASA to the glory
days of Apollo,

00:48.381 --> 00:49.716 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
as you and I remember as kids.

00:49.749 --> 00:53.553 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I want to see NASA go above and
beyond the
glory days of Apollo.

00:53.586 --> 01:01.428 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All that and more
on tonight's
"PBS NewsHour."

01:01.461 --> 01:04.230 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(BREAK)

01:04.264 --> 01:14.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: New tensions
between the United
States and Russia dominated this
day.

01:14.174 --> 01:20.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
America's top diplomat carried
U.S. grievances
over Syria and other issues to
Moscow, while

01:20.246 --> 01:22.949 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
President Trump spoke out in
Washington.

01:22.982 --> 01:27.187 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Our chief foreign affairs
correspondent, Margaret
Warner, has our report.

01:27.220 --> 01:33.693 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: The discord was
on display
at the very outset of Secretary
of State Rex

01:33.726 --> 01:37.197 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tillerson's meetings with
Russian Foreign
Minister Sergei Lavrov.

01:37.230 --> 01:40.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SERGEI LAVROV, Russian Foreign
Minister (through
translator): We have a lot of
questions regarding

01:40.100 --> 01:44.904 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
very ambiguous and as well as
sometimes contradictory
ideas on coming from Washington.

01:44.938 --> 01:49.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Tillerson
acknowledged sharp
differences, and after meeting
privately with

01:49.242 --> 01:53.046 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Russian President Vladimir
Putin, he emerged
with an even grimmer appraisal.

01:53.079 --> 01:56.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
REX TILLERSON, U.S. Secretary of
State: The
current state of U.S.-Russia
relations is

01:56.182 --> 01:58.451 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
at a low point.

01:58.485 --> 02:02.355 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There is a low level of trust
between our
two countries.

02:02.388 --> 02:06.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The world's two foremost nuclear
powers cannot
have this kind of relationship.

02:06.526 --> 02:11.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: The most
immediate trigger
for tensions, a deadly sarin gas
attack in

02:11.397 --> 02:18.538 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Syria last week, and the U.S.
response, a
cruise missile strike on a
Syrian air base.

02:18.571 --> 02:22.942 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Lavrov again denied Russia's
ally the Syrian
government was responsible.

02:22.976 --> 02:28.314 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SERGEI LAVROV (through
translator): We believe
it's necessary to have an
international, unbiased,

02:28.348 --> 02:30.750 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
frank investigation into this
incident.

02:30.783 --> 02:35.288 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There were no signs that would
support the
statement, the allegation that
chemical agents

02:35.321 --> 02:37.056 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
were used there at all.

02:37.090 --> 02:41.261 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Tillerson
insisted again
that Syria's government did
carry out the

02:41.294 --> 02:45.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
attack, and he called again for
Russia to
abandon President Bashar
al-Assad.

02:45.865 --> 02:51.271 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
REX TILLERSON: We do think it's
important
that Assad's departure is done
in an orderly

02:51.304 --> 02:57.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
way, an orderly way, so that
certain interests
and constituencies that he
represents feel

02:57.877 --> 03:03.249 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that they have been represented
at the negotiating
table for a political solution.

03:03.283 --> 03:06.953 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How that occurs, we leave that
to the process
going forward.

03:06.986 --> 03:08.755 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: But in New York
this afternoon:

03:08.788 --> 03:12.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NIKKI HALEY, U.S. Ambassador to
the United
Nations: It is long past time
for Russia to

03:12.192 --> 03:14.194 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
stop covering for Assad.

03:14.227 --> 03:19.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Russia vetoed a
U.N. Security
Council resolution condemning
the gas attack

03:19.666 --> 03:21.100 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in Syria.

03:21.134 --> 03:25.872 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The chill in Moscow today was a
far cry from
the atmosphere a year ago.

03:25.905 --> 03:31.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then-candidate Donald Trump
repeatedly praised
Vladimir Putin during the
campaign, and he

03:31.077 --> 03:36.382 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
suggested a rapprochement with
Russia was
both desirable and possible.

03:36.416 --> 03:42.488 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That all changed with last
week's gas attack
and President Trump's quick
response.

03:42.522 --> 03:47.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Even before the meetings,
President Putin
gave his own pointed assessment
of U.S.-Russia

03:47.660 --> 03:50.063 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
relations today on Russian state
television.

03:50.096 --> 03:53.032 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
VLADIMIR PUTIN, Russian
President (through
translator): It is possible to
say that the

03:53.066 --> 03:58.238 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
level of trust on a working
level, especially
on the military level, it has
not improved,

03:58.271 --> 04:00.073 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
but rather has deteriorated.

04:00.106 --> 04:05.511 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: In turn,
President Trump
had harsh new words for the
Russians and their

04:05.545 --> 04:09.916 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Syrian ally Assad in an
interview that aired
on FOX Business Network.

04:09.949 --> 04:15.355 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP, President of the
United States:
If Russia didn't go in and back
this animal,

04:15.388 --> 04:18.391 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you wouldn't have a problem
right now.

04:18.424 --> 04:25.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Frankly, Putin is backing a
person that's
truly an evil person.

04:25.298 --> 04:27.734 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think it's very bad for
Russia.

04:27.767 --> 04:29.435 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think it's very bad for
mankind.

04:29.469 --> 04:31.471 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's very bad for this world.

04:31.504 --> 04:36.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Mr. Trump
followed up at
a joint White House news
conference with NATO's

04:36.609 --> 04:38.044 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
secretary-general.

04:38.077 --> 04:40.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: Right now, we're
not getting
along with Russia at all.

04:40.713 --> 04:45.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We may be an all-time low in
terms of relationship
with Russia.

04:45.385 --> 04:49.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This has built for a long period
of time,
but we are going to see what
happens.

04:49.522 --> 04:52.692 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Tensions are
over more than
Syria.

04:52.725 --> 04:58.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Moscow, Secretary Tillerson
again criticized
Russia's intervention in
Ukraine, which triggered

04:58.398 --> 05:00.099 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Western sanctions.

05:00.133 --> 05:03.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
REX TILLERSON: Until full
progress is made
under the Minsk accords, the
situation in

05:03.703 --> 05:09.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ukraine will remain an obstacle
to improvement
in relations between the U.S.
and Russia.

05:09.342 --> 05:13.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Lavrov gave no
ground on
Ukraine or charges of Russian
meddling in

05:13.479 --> 05:15.281 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the U.S. election.

05:15.315 --> 05:20.520 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The two men did agree to
establish a working
group to try to stabilize
relations.

05:20.553 --> 05:23.489 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Margaret Warner.

05:23.523 --> 05:28.261 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: In the day's
other news: China's
leader, Xi Jinping, told
President Trump that

05:28.294 --> 05:33.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he's willing to work with the
U.S. to stop
North Korea's nuclear program
peacefully.

05:34.000 --> 05:39.372 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The two men spoke in a
late-night phone call,
after Mr. Trump's Twitter
warning yesterday

05:39.405 --> 05:41.674 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that the U.S. might act alone.

05:41.708 --> 05:46.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Beijing today, the Chinese
Foreign Ministry
said the call was a positive
sign.

05:46.145 --> 05:50.049 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LU KANG, Chinese Foreign
Ministry Spokesman
(through translator): On the
nuclear issue,

05:50.083 --> 05:54.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Xi stated China's
stance that we
abide by the objective of
de-nuclearization

05:54.554 --> 05:59.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on the peninsula, continue to
maintain the
peace and stability on the
peninsula and continue

05:59.492 --> 06:02.261 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to resolve the issue peacefully
via dialogue
and negotiation.

06:02.295 --> 06:05.665 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The U.S. clearly understands
this stance.

06:05.698 --> 06:10.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The phone call
came just days
after the two leaders met in
Florida, and

06:10.470 --> 06:15.708 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
after the president seemed to
tie trade issues
to cooperation on North Korea.

06:15.742 --> 06:21.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, the president said he
will not officially
label China a currency
manipulator.

06:21.047 --> 06:25.218 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He said that today, as he had
promised during
the campaign.

06:25.251 --> 06:30.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mr. Trump tweeted today that the
call with
President Xi was a very good
conversation.

06:30.757 --> 06:35.027 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in an interview that aired
today on FOX
Business News, he also said the
North Korea

06:35.061 --> 06:38.498 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
situation is -- quote -- "not as
simple as
people would think."

06:38.531 --> 06:45.438 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's word that the FBI
obtained a secret
court order last summer to
monitor communications

06:45.471 --> 06:46.706 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of Carter Page.

06:46.739 --> 06:50.009 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was advising the Trump
campaign at the
time.

06:50.042 --> 06:54.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Washington Post reports that
a special
court on intelligence matters
found there

06:54.714 --> 06:58.484 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was reason to believe Page was
acting as a
Russian agent.

06:58.518 --> 07:03.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today on CNN, Page said -- quote
-- "It's
just such a joke that it's
beyond words."

07:03.756 --> 07:09.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Meanwhile, President Trump's
former campaign
chair, Paul Manafort, now says
he is registering

07:09.896 --> 07:12.331 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with the U.S. as a foreign
agent.

07:12.365 --> 07:17.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Associated Press confirmed
today that
his lobbying firm did receive
more than $1

07:17.603 --> 07:21.340 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
million from a pro-Russian
political party
in Ukraine.

07:21.374 --> 07:24.710 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That was in 2007 and 2009.

07:24.744 --> 07:29.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Manafort previously said that
any records
of such payments were
fabricated.

07:29.916 --> 07:35.021 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In South Africa, tens of
thousands turned
out against President Jacob Zuma
today on

07:35.054 --> 07:36.889 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
his 75th birthday.

07:36.923 --> 07:41.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was the latest in a string of
protests
calling for his resignation over
allegations

07:41.828 --> 07:43.863 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of widespread corruption.

07:43.896 --> 07:49.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Demonstrators flooded the main
square today
in the capital, Pretoria,
chanting and carrying

07:49.335 --> 07:50.770 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a mock coffin.

07:50.803 --> 07:55.975 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Meanwhile, Zuma attended a
birthday celebration
outside Johannesburg.

07:56.008 --> 08:01.848 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Back in this country,
Republicans managed
onto hold a U.S. House seat in
Kansas in Tuesday's

08:01.881 --> 08:04.150 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
special congressional election.

08:04.183 --> 08:11.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ron Estes won by just seven
points in a district
that went Republican in November
by 31 points.

08:11.891 --> 08:17.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Democrat James Thompson conceded
defeat last
night, but he said it's a
warning to Republicans

08:17.230 --> 08:19.098 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
everywhere.

08:19.131 --> 08:21.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES THOMPSON (D), Kansas
Congressional Candidate:
We have shown that this district
is not just

08:21.501 --> 08:24.270 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
competitive, but that we can win
it.

08:24.303 --> 08:27.073 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have already shocked this
country.

08:27.106 --> 08:31.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have sent a message that no
Republican
district in this country is
safe.

08:31.844 --> 08:35.915 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The Kansas seat
had been held
by Mike Pompeo.

08:35.948 --> 08:39.252 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
He's now President Trump
director of the CIA.

08:39.285 --> 08:44.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Republicans face three more
special elections
to hold onto seats in Georgia,
Montana and

08:44.390 --> 08:45.725 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
South Carolina.

08:45.758 --> 08:49.428 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Their occupants also joined the
Trump administration.

08:49.462 --> 08:53.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The White House lifted a hiring
freeze on
the federal work force today.

08:53.799 --> 08:57.603 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
President Trump had imposed it
on his first
day in office.

08:57.637 --> 09:02.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now the administration is asking
agencies
to identify cuts that they can
make in their

09:02.909 --> 09:04.744 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
staffs.

09:04.777 --> 09:08.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In economic news, the president
told The Wall
Street Journal that he is
concerned that the

09:08.414 --> 09:13.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
U.S. dollar is getting too
strong and he said
he had not decided whether to
reappoint Janet

09:13.853 --> 09:19.191 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Yellen as chairman of the
Federal Reserve
when her term ends in 2018.

09:19.225 --> 09:24.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average
lost 59 points to close at
20591.

09:24.897 --> 09:28.668 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Nasdaq fell 30, and the S&amp;P
500 slipped
eight.

09:28.701 --> 09:34.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Still to come on the "NewsHour":
I speak to
the head of NATO about how the
alliance should

09:34.640 --> 09:42.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
address today's global threats;
Florida battles
wildfires raging across the
state; make NASA

09:42.648 --> 09:43.883 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
great again?

09:43.916 --> 09:57.563 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- the agency's future under
President Trump;
and much more.

09:57.597 --> 10:02.234 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
As we reported earlier,
President Trump hosted
the NATO secretary-general this
afternoon

10:02.268 --> 10:03.736 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
at the White House.

10:03.769 --> 10:08.174 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And a short time later, I spoke
with Jens
Stoltenberg.

10:08.207 --> 10:11.510 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mr. Secretary-General, welcome
to the "NewsHour."

10:11.544 --> 10:16.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We heard President Trump say
today that relations
between the United States and
Russia may be

10:16.816 --> 10:20.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at their lowest point since the
end of the
Cold War.

10:20.453 --> 10:24.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Would you say the same thing
about relations
between NATO and Russia right
now?

10:24.457 --> 10:27.226 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JENS STOLTENBERG, NATO
Secretary-General:
At least the relationship is
difficult.

10:27.259 --> 10:35.334 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that reflects that we see a
more assertive
Russia, which has implemented a
very significant

10:35.368 --> 10:41.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
military buildup over several
years, and a
Russia which has used military
force against

10:41.507 --> 10:44.076 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
neighbors, especially Ukraine.

10:44.110 --> 10:52.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And NATO is responding to that
with the high
readiness of our forces, with
the biggest

10:52.151 --> 10:55.921 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
reinforcement to our collective
defense since
the end of the Cold War.

10:55.955 --> 11:03.062 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the same time, we say that we
are seeking
to avoid a new Cold War, avoid a
new arms

11:03.095 --> 11:07.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
race, and, therefore, we
continue to work
for a more constructive
relationship with

11:07.533 --> 11:09.735 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Russia, including political
dialogue with
Russia.

11:09.769 --> 11:14.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, how do you
prevent it
from becoming just a
oneupmanship?

11:14.340 --> 11:15.708 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Because you're right.

11:15.741 --> 11:19.612 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Russians have sent more
troops, move material
to their border.

11:19.645 --> 11:24.350 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NATO is now doing the same thing
on its eastern
border.

11:24.383 --> 11:27.853 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How does this thing just -- how
do you keep
it from spiraling out of
control?

11:27.887 --> 11:33.526 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENS STOLTENBERG: Partly by
making sure that
what NATO does is proportionate,
defensive.

11:33.559 --> 11:42.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, therefore, we are deploying
battle groups,
battalions, which we consider
necessary to

11:42.735 --> 11:49.675 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
convey a message of deterrence,
credible deterrence,
that if one NATO ally is
attacked, it will

11:49.709 --> 11:52.411 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
trigger a whole response from
the whole alliance.

11:52.445 --> 12:01.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, at the same time, we have
been able to
convene last three meetings of
-- in what

12:01.287 --> 12:05.758 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we call the NATO-Russia council
after two
years without any meetings.

12:05.791 --> 12:09.628 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this council is a platform
where NATO
and Russia meets.

12:09.662 --> 12:13.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We discuss issues like Ukraine,
like Afghanistan,
and so on.

12:13.799 --> 12:15.601 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

12:15.634 --> 12:17.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENS STOLTENBERG: And that's a
way to keep
the channels for political
dialogue open and

12:17.336 --> 12:18.704 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to keep the tensions down.

12:18.738 --> 12:22.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You did just from
the meeting
with President Trump.

12:22.408 --> 12:28.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He spent months and months in
his campaign
for president and even since
then criticizing

12:28.280 --> 12:35.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATO, criticizing its role, at
times even
asking whether NATO was
obsolete.

12:35.654 --> 12:40.760 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Why do you think his -- or do
you think his
view of NATO has changed, and,
if so, why?

12:40.793 --> 12:44.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENS STOLTENBERG: I welcome the
fact that
he has clearly stated today that
NATO is not

12:44.930 --> 12:46.098 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
obsolete.

12:46.132 --> 12:50.269 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think, also, that reflects
that NATO
is adapting.

12:50.302 --> 12:55.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATO is the most successful
alliance in history
because we have been able to
change, to adapt

12:55.474 --> 12:57.176 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
when the world is changing.

12:57.209 --> 13:03.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And now NATO is stepping up its
effort in
the global fight against
terrorism, and we

13:03.215 --> 13:07.987 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
are responding to a more
assertive Russia
with an increase of our
collective defense,

13:08.020 --> 13:11.690 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with more presence in the
eastern part of
the alliance.

13:11.724 --> 13:18.898 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, as long as NATO changes when
the world
is changing, we will be very
important for

13:18.931 --> 13:21.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the security of all our allies,
including
the United States.

13:22.001 --> 13:27.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, you did
note today that
NATO members are increasing
their contributions

13:27.873 --> 13:31.977 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the alliance, as President
Trump has been
calling for them to do.

13:32.011 --> 13:36.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Are you confident, though, that
that is going
to continue in the way that you
and President

13:37.016 --> 13:38.717 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Trump say that it needs to?

13:38.751 --> 13:44.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENS STOLTENBERG: I expect it to
continue,
because all 28 allies have
agreed that they

13:44.790 --> 13:49.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
will stop the cuts in defense
spending, gradual
increase, and then move towards
spending 2

13:49.461 --> 13:53.365 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
percent of GDP, gross domestic
product, on
defense.

13:53.399 --> 13:58.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the encouraging thing is
that we have
seen that we have turned a
corner.

13:58.938 --> 14:04.043 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After many, many years of
decline in defense
spending across Europe and
Canada, in 2016,

14:04.076 --> 14:07.246 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we saw the first significant
increase.

14:07.279 --> 14:11.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We still have a long way to go,
but at least
European allies have kind of
started move

14:11.851 --> 14:13.953 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the right direction.

14:13.986 --> 14:17.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You also spoke
today, Mr. Secretary-General,
about the fight against
terrorism, the global

14:17.623 --> 14:22.094 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
fight, and you said NATO has a
larger role
to play in that regard.

14:22.127 --> 14:24.430 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What exactly did you have in
mind?

14:24.463 --> 14:29.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENS STOLTENBERG: Many things,
but perhaps
the most important thing is to
build local

14:29.134 --> 14:35.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
capacity, meaning train local
forces, build
the local defense institutions,
defense ministries,

14:35.541 --> 14:41.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
command and control, because, in
the long
run, it is expected that local
forces are

14:41.046 --> 14:46.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
stabilizing their own country,
fighting terrorism
themselves, instead of NATO
deploying a large

14:46.919 --> 14:49.521 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
number of combat troops in
combat operations.

14:49.555 --> 14:53.192 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's NATO's experience
from Afghanistan.

14:53.225 --> 14:54.894 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We have ended our combat
operations there.

14:54.927 --> 14:56.762 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

14:56.795 --> 15:00.599 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENS STOLTENBERG: We train the
local Afghans
to fight terrorism themselves
and think, in

15:00.633 --> 15:03.369 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the long run, that's a much more
sustainable
approach.

15:03.402 --> 15:07.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But that is -- I
think most
observers now see Afghanistan as
slipping

15:07.806 --> 15:09.174 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
back into chaos.

15:09.208 --> 15:14.780 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Taliban is stronger than
many people say
that it's been in years.

15:14.813 --> 15:16.815 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ISIS now has a foothold.

15:16.849 --> 15:21.453 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But you're saying that that's
not a reason
for NATO to get involved?

15:21.487 --> 15:25.891 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENS STOLTENBERG: I'm saying
that there are
many difficult challenges in
Afghanistan.

15:25.925 --> 15:27.793 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And we still have Taliban.

15:27.826 --> 15:33.399 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We still have terrorist
organizations there,
and we will see violence and we
will see conflict

15:33.432 --> 15:36.068 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
there also in the coming years,.

15:36.101 --> 15:39.238 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But we have achieved at least
two important
things.

15:39.271 --> 15:44.576 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Afghanistan is no longer a safe
haven for
international terrorists.

15:44.610 --> 15:50.449 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have a strong Afghan army,
which is fighting
the terrorists and Taliban.

15:50.482 --> 15:56.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the second thing is that
they are able
to do that without us being
there to conduct

15:56.088 --> 15:57.856 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the combat operations.

15:57.890 --> 16:02.761 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What NATO troops are doing in
Afghanistan
is to train, assist and advise
Afghans, but

16:02.795 --> 16:04.463 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they are actually doing the
fighting.

16:04.496 --> 16:09.134 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They are actually taking the
responsibility
for the security in their own
country.

16:09.168 --> 16:14.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is a great achievement,
compared
to what we saw just a few years
ago, when

16:14.506 --> 16:17.810 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NATO troops had to conduct the
combat operations
fighting the Taliban.

16:17.843 --> 16:20.479 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you think
that war going
in the right direction, though?

16:20.512 --> 16:27.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENS STOLTENBERG: I think it is
a very important
step in the right direction that
the Afghans

16:27.453 --> 16:32.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have taken over responsibility
for the security
in their own country, and NATO
being able

16:32.758 --> 16:35.361 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to end its combat presence in
Afghanistan.

16:35.394 --> 16:43.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But,of course, there are still
many, many
uncertainties, challenges and
difficulties

16:43.902 --> 16:45.404 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in Afghanistan.

16:45.437 --> 16:49.742 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But we have to enable the
Afghans to manage
those challenges themselves.

16:49.775 --> 16:51.910 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We cannot solve all the problems
for the Afghans.

16:51.944 --> 16:55.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally, Mr.
Secretary-General,
a question about Turkey, which,
as you know,

16:55.748 --> 17:00.652 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
is just days away from a
referendum that would
grant sweeping additional powers
to President

17:00.686 --> 17:06.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Erdogan, essentially making him
-- or allowing
him to be immune from any
oversight by the

17:06.191 --> 17:08.494 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
parliament or by the courts.

17:08.527 --> 17:12.564 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, there are those who
are critics
of his who are saying that this
is going to

17:12.598 --> 17:20.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
lead to if it passes is NATO's
second largest
standing army controlled, in
essence, by someone

17:20.939 --> 17:23.942 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
who has dictatorial powers.

17:23.976 --> 17:26.745 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How comfortable would you be
with that?

17:26.779 --> 17:33.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENS STOLTENBERG: Turkey's a
valued ally,
important ally for NATO, not the
least because

17:33.585 --> 17:42.261 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of its strategic geographic
location, bordering
Syria and Iraq and close to
Russia and the

17:42.294 --> 17:44.063 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Black Sea.

17:44.096 --> 17:49.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we have to remember Turkey
has suffered
many terrorist attacks, a failed
coup attempt

17:49.201 --> 17:55.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in July of last year, and is the
ally most
affected by the instability, the
violence

17:55.574 --> 17:58.110 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
we see in Syria and Iraq.

17:58.143 --> 18:04.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Turkey has, of course, the right
to protect
itself against terrorism,
against attacks,

18:04.216 --> 18:12.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but I expect it to be done in a
way which
is in accordance with the rule
of law, democratic

18:12.424 --> 18:14.226 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
values.

18:14.259 --> 18:19.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is something I have
expressed several
times in meetings with the
Turkish leaders.

18:19.965 --> 18:24.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Jens Stoltenberg,
who is the
secretary-general for NATO, we
thank you very

18:24.470 --> 18:25.737 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
much.

18:25.771 --> 18:33.612 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JENS STOLTENBERG: Thank you so
much.

18:33.645 --> 18:40.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: More than 100
wildfires are
burning in and around Florida,
and the state

18:41.019 --> 18:44.156 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is expecting a difficult fire
season ahead.

18:44.189 --> 18:47.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Yesterday, the governor declared
a state of
emergency there.

18:47.659 --> 18:49.261 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
William Brangham has the latest.

18:49.294 --> 18:54.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Over 70,000
acres have burned
across the state since February.

18:54.399 --> 18:56.135 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the fires are not just in
one spot.

18:56.168 --> 18:58.637 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're located in all corners
of the state.

18:58.670 --> 19:02.341 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is also occurring while
Florida is dealing
with a major drought.

19:02.374 --> 19:07.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jim Karels is the director of
the Florida
Forest Service and a 32-year
veteran of fighting

19:07.613 --> 19:08.580 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
fires.

19:08.614 --> 19:09.948 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He joins us from Tallahassee.

19:09.982 --> 19:11.750 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Welcome to the "NewsHour."

19:11.783 --> 19:14.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jim, I wonder if you could just
give us a
sense of how things are in
Florida right now.

19:14.553 --> 19:16.355 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JIM KARELS, Director, Florida
Forest Service:
Dry.

19:16.388 --> 19:20.259 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The peninsula of Florida is --
especially
South and Central Florida,
extremely dry right

19:20.292 --> 19:21.827 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
now.

19:21.860 --> 19:25.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's drying out as you go
north all the
way to the Georgia-Florida line.

19:25.998 --> 19:29.735 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: We mentioned
you're also
dealing with a drought at the
same time.

19:29.768 --> 19:32.604 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How much is that a contributing
factor to
all of this?

19:32.638 --> 19:38.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JIM KARELS: A big contributing
factor, in
that, you know, we had some late
freezes,

19:38.777 --> 19:43.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
didn't have much of a winter
here in Florida,
but we did have a freeze late
into February,

19:43.582 --> 19:45.350 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
early March.

19:45.384 --> 19:49.454 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And it went down to
South-Central Florida,
and then it really didn't rain
after that.

19:49.488 --> 19:51.590 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So you have got that dry
vegetation.

19:51.623 --> 19:58.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have got -- low rainfalls
were really
since about January, kind of a
La Nina effect

19:58.897 --> 20:01.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that we tend to get every few
years in Florida.

20:01.867 --> 20:08.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And now we're into our normally
dry season,
April, May, parts of Florida,
early June,

20:08.140 --> 20:10.642 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
where we're normally dry anyway.

20:10.676 --> 20:17.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that increases the whole
situation, where
it makes it very easy for fires
to start,

20:17.349 --> 20:18.784 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
makes it very easy for fires to
spread.

20:18.817 --> 20:21.987 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: This is still
the beginning
of your fire season.

20:22.020 --> 20:24.456 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do you have any sense of what
the longer-term
forecast is?

20:24.489 --> 20:26.258 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What does it look like coming
down the road?

20:26.291 --> 20:30.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JIM KARELS: Well, we have got a
couple forecasts
out of -- one, our National Fire
Center in

20:30.796 --> 20:32.631 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Boise.

20:32.664 --> 20:39.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that pretty much paints a
red target on
Florida probably through April,
May, and June.

20:39.371 --> 20:46.111 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The NOAA forecasts show the
drought expanding
into some parts of the state
into the same

20:46.144 --> 20:47.913 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
period, into April, May, June.

20:47.946 --> 20:50.949 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's normally our dry period.

20:50.983 --> 20:59.358 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Along with how dry we already
are, it really
paints a picture that we have
got a pretty

20:59.391 --> 21:01.893 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
intense fire season in front of
us.

21:01.927 --> 21:03.462 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We are very busy already.

21:03.495 --> 21:05.464 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We're busy early.

21:05.497 --> 21:09.735 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we're drier than normal
early, as it is
in early April right now.

21:09.768 --> 21:15.941 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we really expect to probably
have to fight
fire all the way to June, maybe
even July.

21:15.974 --> 21:18.076 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it tends to move up the
state.

21:18.110 --> 21:20.979 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Our worst right now is South
Florida.

21:21.013 --> 21:24.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It moves to Central Florida, and
then it moves
to North Florida as it kind of
closes out

21:24.916 --> 21:25.917 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
our fire seasons.

21:25.951 --> 21:29.087 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And over 100
fires.

21:29.121 --> 21:34.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Can you give us a sense of what
is causing
so many different simultaneous
fires?

21:34.526 --> 21:39.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JIM KARELS: Well, right now, the
majority
of our fires are human-caused,
probably 90

21:39.064 --> 21:41.066 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
percent of them.

21:41.099 --> 21:42.901 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Various different things.

21:42.934 --> 21:47.406 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Some of it is yard trash
burning, where people
are cleaning, spring cleaning,
and they're

21:47.439 --> 21:49.241 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
burning their leaves.

21:49.274 --> 21:53.412 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Some of it is vehicles,
catalytic convertors,
that type, or equipment working
in the woods

21:53.445 --> 21:55.647 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or the wildlands.

21:55.681 --> 21:57.783 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Some of it is arson, incendiary.

21:57.816 --> 21:59.718 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Have some issues with that.

21:59.751 --> 22:03.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then this past weekend, we
got some lightning,
so we're starting to see the
lightning fires

22:03.922 --> 22:05.724 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
evolve as well.

22:05.757 --> 22:09.761 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Most Americans
think of
fires out West in the very dry
brush and forestland

22:09.795 --> 22:14.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
we see out there, but I
understand that the
type of vegetation that is
burning and the

22:14.099 --> 22:16.101 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
way it burns in Florida is quite
different.

22:16.134 --> 22:18.236 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JIM KARELS: It is.

22:18.270 --> 22:23.775 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Fire evolved under fire, so it
was constant
fire prior to humans.

22:23.809 --> 22:28.380 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the vegetation tends to be
more waxy,
more resinous.

22:28.413 --> 22:31.283 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What we say is, in Florida,
green burns.

22:31.316 --> 22:33.085 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's different from the West.

22:33.118 --> 22:39.558 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The West, the fuels tend to be
very cured,
very dry, very -- essentially
dead, where,

22:39.591 --> 22:44.262 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
down here, you come in here and
you look at
our vegetation, you think that's
not going

22:44.296 --> 22:46.598 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to burn, and it's just the
opposite.

22:46.631 --> 22:49.668 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then it burns under a lot
higher humidity.

22:49.701 --> 22:54.906 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Our fires can burn very
intensely all the
way up to 40, 50 percent
humidity.

22:54.940 --> 22:57.476 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In the West, it tends to be 20
percent or
below.

22:57.509 --> 23:00.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: With all these
different
fires across the state, what is
the danger

23:00.979 --> 23:02.614 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to the human population?

23:02.647 --> 23:07.085 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JIM KARELS: As you know,
Florida's got a big
population, about 20 million
people.

23:07.119 --> 23:14.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, just about every fire we
have impacts
what we call the urban
interface, or homes,

23:14.459 --> 23:15.694 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
structures.

23:15.727 --> 23:19.498 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so far this year, we have
evacuated over
1,800 homes.

23:19.531 --> 23:21.466 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And we lost 27.

23:21.500 --> 23:30.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we saved a lot, impacted a
good number
of people in their daily lives
from the wildfires.

23:30.308 --> 23:36.314 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the other thing in Florida
that it really
experiences is the impact on the
roadways.

23:36.348 --> 23:38.717 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We get smoke on the highways.

23:38.750 --> 23:44.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
With all those people and with a
lot of tourists
moving through the state, the
roads become

23:44.289 --> 23:46.691 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
dangerous when the visibility
gets down low.

23:46.725 --> 23:49.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right, Jim
Karels of
the Florida Forest Service,
thank you very

23:49.828 --> 23:50.796 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
much.

23:50.829 --> 23:51.797 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And good luck down there.

23:51.830 --> 23:54.699 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JIM KARELS: Thank you.

23:54.733 --> 24:01.773 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

24:01.807 --> 24:08.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": a
new investigation
finds nearly 2,000 allegations
of sexual abuse

24:08.213 --> 24:15.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by U.N. peacekeepers; what's
left in an ancient
Assyrian city after years of
ISIS rule; and

24:15.954 --> 24:22.961 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
"The Refugees," fictional
stories of immigration,
identity and love.

24:22.994 --> 24:28.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But first: How will NASA's
mission change
under President Trump and a
Republican Congress

24:28.667 --> 24:31.503 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that helps decide where money
should go?

24:31.536 --> 24:37.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some big changes could be in
store for space
exploration and the missions set
into place

24:37.242 --> 24:40.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
now that could stretch well
beyond the Trump
era.

24:40.879 --> 24:45.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Miles O'Brien has the story for
our weekly
segment about the Leading Edge
of science

24:45.217 --> 24:47.052 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and technology.

24:47.085 --> 24:53.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The balcony at
Congressman
John Culberson's office on
Capitol Hill offers

24:53.091 --> 24:59.130 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
a sweeping panorama of
Washington, but the
Republican from Houston is
usually looking

24:59.164 --> 25:02.634 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
higher.

25:02.667 --> 25:06.071 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

25:06.104 --> 25:09.474 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN CULBERSON (R), Texas:
There's Mercury.

25:09.508 --> 25:10.475 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mars is going to appear right
here.

25:10.509 --> 25:11.476 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We go this way, there's Orion.

25:11.510 --> 25:12.944 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Sirius is going to appear right
here.

25:12.978 --> 25:14.412 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Culberson has
more than a hobby-level
interest in space.

25:14.446 --> 25:17.949 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
He chairs the House
Appropriations Subcommittee
that oversees NASA.

25:17.983 --> 25:23.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In his ninth term, he is riding
high, as the
Trump administration embraces
his strategy

25:23.722 --> 25:25.357 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for exploring space.

25:25.390 --> 25:26.691 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

25:26.725 --> 25:28.560 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN CULBERSON: NASA has been
underfunded
for far too long.

25:28.593 --> 25:33.465 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have been short-sticked by
previous administrations,
this past administration.

25:33.498 --> 25:39.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I'm very excited and pleased
to see President
Trump recommend enough funding
for NASA as

25:39.471 --> 25:40.805 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
a whole.

25:40.839 --> 25:43.842 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: President Trump
apparently
sees NASA as a priority.

25:43.875 --> 25:47.279 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's made passing references to
space in his
inaugural address.

25:47.312 --> 25:52.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP, President of the
United States:
We stand at the birth of a new
millennium,

25:52.417 --> 25:55.353 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ready to unlock the mysteries of
space.

25:55.387 --> 25:58.023 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: And in his speech
to Congress.

25:58.056 --> 26:02.961 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
DONALD TRUMP: American
footprints on distant
worlds are not too big a dream.

26:02.994 --> 26:08.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: The Trump
administration is
proposing only a 1 percent
reduction in NASA's

26:08.366 --> 26:10.869 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
$19 billion annual budget.

26:10.902 --> 26:14.673 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Hardest-hit programs are science
and education.

26:14.706 --> 26:20.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But at a time when the federal
scientific
enterprise is facing deep,
unprecedented cuts,

26:20.412 --> 26:23.782 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the space agency may have dodged
a missile.

26:23.815 --> 26:29.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mr. Trump's space advisers
include former
House Speaker Newt Gingrich and
former Congressman

26:29.220 --> 26:33.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Bob Walker, who served as
chairman of the
subcommittee that oversees NASA.

26:33.391 --> 26:38.129 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT WALKER (R), Former U.S.
Congressman:
Newt has had several
conversations with Trump

26:38.163 --> 26:41.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and with Vice President Pence.

26:41.566 --> 26:45.437 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And both of them are space
cadets.

26:45.470 --> 26:50.976 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there are other fairly
high-ranking people
in the White House who are also
space cadets.

26:51.009 --> 26:55.347 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: In this case,
space cadet is
a compliment.

26:55.380 --> 26:59.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Walker says the White House
would like NASA
to get out of low Earth orbit,
leaving that

26:59.517 --> 27:02.454 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
realm to private enterprise.

27:02.487 --> 27:08.259 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Beyond that, the space agency
takes a role
that increases with the distance
from Earth.

27:08.293 --> 27:11.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The administration is also
focused on humans
returning to the moon.

27:11.930 --> 27:15.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT WALKER: I think the moon
is an important
step on the way to Mars.

27:15.634 --> 27:23.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think you have to have some
experience in
a very hostile environment where
you develop

27:23.508 --> 27:29.447 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some of the technologies that
you need to
exist on Mars before you
actually head to

27:29.481 --> 27:31.216 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Mars.

27:31.249 --> 27:33.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: For Congressman
Culberson,
that is well and good, but he
believes the

27:33.885 --> 27:41.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
most important green-lit mission
is aimed
at this object, the icy moon of
Jupiter, Europa.

27:41.459 --> 27:47.265 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Europa Clipper was approved
by the Obama
administration and Congress in
2015, more

27:47.298 --> 27:52.904 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
than 10 years after Culberson
began obsessively
pushing NASA to go there.

27:52.937 --> 27:55.907 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Europa has always fascinated
him.

27:55.940 --> 27:58.543 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Beneath the ice is a salty
ocean.

27:58.576 --> 28:00.078 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
How much?

28:00.111 --> 28:03.748 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He answers the question with a
poster on foam
core he keeps in his office.

28:03.782 --> 28:05.483 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

28:05.517 --> 28:08.553 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN CULBERSON: This is all the
water on Earth,
both fresh and salt, and all the
water on

28:08.586 --> 28:10.422 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Europa.

28:10.455 --> 28:13.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is a free-floating ice
shell, and there's
two to three times more water on
Europa than

28:13.892 --> 28:15.760 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
there is on Earth.

28:15.794 --> 28:19.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Scientists find
this tantalizing,
because, no matter how far down
they explore

28:19.364 --> 28:22.834 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in our oceans, they find all
kinds of living
creatures.

28:22.867 --> 28:28.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KEVIN PETER HAND, NASA: And with
that much
water out there today in our
solar system,

28:28.540 --> 28:30.909 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that begs the question, could
there be life
within that ocean?

28:30.942 --> 28:37.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Jet propulsion
laboratory astrobiologist
Kevin Hand is in line to be the
project scientist

28:37.282 --> 28:42.353 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for a NASA mission to land on
Europa by about
2030.

28:42.387 --> 28:46.224 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That lander would be preceded by
an orbiter
slated for launch in 2022.

28:46.257 --> 28:52.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The orbiter is designed to
capture stunning
imagery and detailed science
about the salts

28:53.031 --> 28:58.603 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and any organic compounds on the
surface,
and use radar to look beneath at
the boundary

28:58.636 --> 29:01.072 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
between the ice and the ocean.

29:01.106 --> 29:03.475 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
All of this will help them
determine where
to land.

29:03.508 --> 29:08.113 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KEVIN PETER HAND: We'd love to
melt through
the ice and reach the ocean
directly, but,

29:08.146 --> 29:15.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
based on the evidence we have,
Europa's ice
shell does serve as a relatively
good window

29:15.420 --> 29:17.188 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
into the ocean below.

29:17.222 --> 29:23.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We could, perhaps by sampling
the surface,
also be sampling ocean material,
and thereby

29:23.361 --> 29:28.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
also be potentially grabbing a
sample that
could have some little Europa
organisms.

29:28.099 --> 29:33.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: But, for many
years, NASA didn't
seem interested in Europan
krill.

29:33.905 --> 29:39.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The NASA administrator under
George W. Bush,
Mike Griffin, thwarted
Culberson's first attempt

29:39.844 --> 29:41.479 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to land on Europa.

29:41.513 --> 29:44.749 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was a mission called the
Jupiter Icy Moons
Orbiter.

29:44.783 --> 29:50.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it was canceled in 2006 to
pay for completion
of the International Space
Station.

29:50.121 --> 29:51.823 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

29:51.856 --> 29:53.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN CULBERSON: When Mike
Griffin canceled
the Europa mission last decade,
it scarred

29:53.458 --> 29:57.962 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
me so badly, I swore I wouldn't
let the bureaucrats
cancel this mission again.

29:57.996 --> 30:04.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, today, the Europa orbiter
and lander is
the only mission it is still
illegal for NASA

30:04.335 --> 30:05.303 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
not to fly.

30:05.336 --> 30:07.438 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: You heard right.

30:07.472 --> 30:13.278 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Culberson made the Europa
orbiter and lander
missions the law of the land in
2015.

30:13.311 --> 30:16.915 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But exploring Europa is
challenging and expensive.

30:16.948 --> 30:22.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NASA managers complained their
plate was already
too full with the space station
and an extensive

30:22.220 --> 30:27.025 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
campaign to explore Mars.

30:27.058 --> 30:33.298 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And the focus on Mars is
sustained by the
goal of eventually sending
humans to the surface.

30:33.331 --> 30:39.037 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Europa is only a destination for
robots, and
hearty ones at that.

30:39.070 --> 30:43.708 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Lethal radiation levels ensure
no human can
ever visit.

30:43.741 --> 30:49.314 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It makes the mission less
attractive to the
powerful astronaut side of the
House at NASA.

30:49.347 --> 30:53.451 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But in this war of the worlds,
Mars has met
its match.

30:53.484 --> 30:58.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT WALKER: The fact that
people are talking
about Europa right now is a
result of Chairman

30:58.590 --> 31:00.825 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Culberson's interest in it.

31:00.859 --> 31:07.065 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the fact is that he has
caused NASA to
say, if that's what Chairman
Culberson wants,

31:07.098 --> 31:08.967 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that's what Chairman Culberson
gets.

31:09.000 --> 31:09.968 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

31:10.001 --> 31:13.004 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Culberson isn't
stopping there.

31:13.037 --> 31:18.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He has written a 50-year plan
for NASA that
includes a spacecraft that can
go 10 percent

31:18.676 --> 31:24.649 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the speed of light for
humanity's first interstellar
mission to the nearest
Earth-like star.

31:24.682 --> 31:29.520 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The launch date is 2069, 100
years after the
first moon landing.

31:29.554 --> 31:31.456 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

31:31.489 --> 31:33.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN CULBERSON: I have always
wanted to restore
NASA to the glory days of
Apollo, as you and

31:33.524 --> 31:34.859 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I remember as kids.

31:34.893 --> 31:38.529 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I want to see NASA go above and
beyond the
glory days of Apollo.

31:38.563 --> 31:42.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Culberson is all
about making
NASA great again.

31:42.467 --> 31:46.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
