is to see it just bulldozed,
just -- it's

41:50.074 --> 41:51.141 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
gone.

41:51.175 --> 41:54.745 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The iconic image of Nimrud is
with the ziggurat.

41:54.778 --> 41:59.250 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MARCIA BIGGS: For Tobin
Hartnell, this was
an experience he'd waited for.

41:59.283 --> 42:05.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He studied Assyria and its
ancient capital
for 15 years, yet he had never
seen it.

42:05.055 --> 42:10.761 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He took a job teaching at the
American University
of Iraq in 2014 and was just
about to move

42:10.794 --> 42:13.063 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
his family when ISIS swept
through the region.

42:13.097 --> 42:18.202 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TOBIN HARTNELL: We got basically
the e-mail
or a call, in my case, an
e-mail, saying,

42:18.235 --> 42:22.573 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
well, you don't have to accept
the job because
ISIS has just taken Mosul.

42:22.606 --> 42:27.344 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My wife and I, we talked about
it, we're going,
because, as archaeologists, this
is where

42:27.378 --> 42:29.146 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the work needs to be.

42:29.179 --> 42:31.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: And how does it
feel to be walking
down these steps for the first
time?

42:31.916 --> 42:34.051 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TOBIN HARTNELL: I mean, it's
bittersweet.

42:34.084 --> 42:40.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is an incredible site that
I have been
looking forward to going to for
over 20 years.

42:40.658 --> 42:42.459 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And look at it.

42:42.493 --> 42:46.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, walking over rubble, the
destruction
that ISIS has left has turned
one of the most

42:46.997 --> 42:51.368 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
magnificent palaces of Assyria
into a disaster
zone.

42:51.402 --> 42:56.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: The gates of the
famous Northwest
Palace, once the home of
magnificent winged

42:56.073 --> 42:59.643 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
bulls, reduced to rubble, its
walls bare.

42:59.677 --> 43:05.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TOBIN HARTNELL: I never got to
see the gate
as it should be seen, that these
bulls welcomed

43:05.049 --> 43:06.817 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
you to the palace.

43:06.850 --> 43:10.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LEILA SALIH, Archaeologist:
Every Assyrian
gates have a couple of winged
bulls, so we

43:10.821 --> 43:12.756 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
cannot imagine the gates without
them.

43:12.790 --> 43:16.060 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: It wasn't Leila
Salih's first
time here.

43:16.093 --> 43:18.629 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She was 14 years old when she
first visited
Nimrud.

43:18.662 --> 43:23.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LEILA SALIH: To be honest with
you, at that
time, we didn't care about
historical things

43:23.934 --> 43:26.136 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
or ancient civilization things.

43:26.170 --> 43:29.340 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We just would like to escape out
of school.

43:29.373 --> 43:36.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what I can remember, the
huge figure of
lamassu and the facade of that
palace.

43:36.680 --> 43:40.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: But this was a
happy place for
you to come with friends and
family?

43:40.751 --> 43:41.952 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LEILA SALIH: Of course.

43:41.986 --> 43:44.822 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a very happy and wonderful,
amazing place
for us.

43:44.855 --> 43:49.259 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Salih is from
nearby Mosul,
much of it still controlled by
ISIS.

43:49.293 --> 43:53.130 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She fled in 2014 with only a
handbag.

43:53.163 --> 43:58.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She was the curator for the
Mosul Museum,
which ISIS was seen destroying
in these videos.

43:58.802 --> 44:04.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yet, even with the widespread
damage, both
she and Hartnell say there is
still hope for

44:04.541 --> 44:05.909 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Nimrud.

44:05.943 --> 44:12.082 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LEILA SALIH: I thought we lost
everything,
as you see in the video.

44:12.116 --> 44:16.320 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But after I visited Nimrud, yes,
there are
some positive signs for us.

44:16.353 --> 44:20.557 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TOBIN HARTNELL: You can see the
wings of the
bull here.

44:20.591 --> 44:25.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: One source of
hope, large chunks
of the rubble still exist, which
makes restoration

44:25.462 --> 44:27.264 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
easier.

44:27.297 --> 44:31.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And several of the original
lamassu bulls
excavated in the 19th century
have been living

44:31.735 --> 44:35.372 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for decades in museums in London
and New York.

44:35.406 --> 44:39.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
While the displaying of Iraq's
antiquities
abroad may have been
controversial, for the

44:39.443 --> 44:44.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
man whose childhood was spent
among the ruins,
this actually provides some
comfort.

44:44.148 --> 44:48.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KHALID AL-JABBOURI (through
translator): Maybe
we Iraqis felt hurt when we saw
our monuments

44:48.952 --> 44:50.888 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
displayed outside of Iraq.

44:50.921 --> 44:53.123 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We get hurt because it's our
civilization.

44:53.157 --> 44:57.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when ISIS occupied the city,
I felt relieved
that Nimrud monuments had been
transported

44:57.928 --> 45:00.431 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
outside of Iraq and remain
protected.

45:00.464 --> 45:03.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And we are proud of them
wherever they are.

45:03.133 --> 45:09.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: And after over 100
years of
excavation, Hartnell says less
than a quarter

45:09.707 --> 45:11.842 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the ancient city was actually
unearthed.

45:11.875 --> 45:18.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TOBIN HARTNELL: There's still
1,000, 2,000
years of history underneath that
palace.

45:18.315 --> 45:20.150 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The whole city is waiting to be
discovered.

45:20.184 --> 45:24.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: So, in some ways,
this being
razed will allow archaeologists
to see what's

45:24.788 --> 45:26.657 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
underneath?

45:26.690 --> 45:29.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TOBIN HARTNELL: If, when we're
doing our cleanup
and restoration, we take some
more time to

45:30.027 --> 45:36.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
dig down, we will find many more
discoveries
from what happened before the
empire, what

45:36.867 --> 45:41.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
happened in the 10th, 11th, 12th
centuries,
which are also great periods in
Mesopotamian

45:41.538 --> 45:42.506 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
history.

45:42.539 --> 45:44.408 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And yet we know almost nothing.

45:44.441 --> 45:47.945 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: For Hartnell,
amidst the sobering
reality of finally checking
Nimrud off his

45:47.978 --> 45:51.715 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
bucket list, comfort in
determining what needs
be done.

45:51.749 --> 45:58.355 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TOBIN HARTNELL: You have to see,
be there,
see the destruction to start to
formulate

45:58.388 --> 45:59.356 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
a plan.

45:59.389 --> 46:01.191 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Archaeologists need to be on the
ground.

46:01.225 --> 46:06.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I won't say a dream comes
true, but it
was on my dream list before it
was destroyed,

46:06.797 --> 46:08.432 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and for very good reason.

46:08.465 --> 46:11.235 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is a fantastic place, and I
think it
will be again.

46:11.268 --> 46:16.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: As the sun sets on
Nimrud, it's
a promise that a new day will
come.

46:16.640 --> 46:23.747 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Marcia Biggs in
Nimrud, Northern Iraq.

46:23.781 --> 46:34.057 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now the latest
addition to
the "NewsHour" Bookshelf.

46:34.091 --> 46:39.296 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's "The Refugees," a short
story collection
from last year's winner of the
Pulitzer Prize

46:39.329 --> 46:41.098 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for Fiction.

46:41.131 --> 46:45.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown talked with Viet
Thanh Nguyen
at this year's Conference of the
Association

46:45.269 --> 46:49.606 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of American Writers and writing
programs here
in Washington, D.C.

46:49.640 --> 46:55.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I wanted to start
with -- maybe
it's a basic question, but it's
the word refugees,

46:55.779 --> 46:57.648 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
because it's an important one to
you.

46:57.681 --> 46:58.649 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VIET THANH NGUYEN, Author, "The
Refugees":
Right.

46:58.682 --> 47:00.551 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What does it
mean?

47:00.584 --> 47:02.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VIET THANH NGUYEN: To be a
refugee, especially
in our contemporary moment, is
to be different

47:02.986 --> 47:04.721 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
than an immigrant.

47:04.755 --> 47:08.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think immigrants are somewhat
acceptable
to Europe and the United States,
but refugees

47:08.992 --> 47:11.361 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are the unwanted from wherever
they come from.

47:11.395 --> 47:15.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they're often unwanted where
they come
to, and especially in the United
States.

47:15.132 --> 47:17.734 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think Americans think it's
un-American to
be a refugee.

47:17.768 --> 47:21.672 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, it's actually really
important for me
to continually assert, I am a
refugee, I write

47:21.705 --> 47:26.777 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about refugees, and that we need
to think
about the necessity of opening
our doors and

47:26.810 --> 47:28.612 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
welcoming refugees in.

47:28.645 --> 47:34.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Living between
worlds, never
leaving one behind fully, why is
that so much

47:34.451 --> 47:38.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
harder for the refugee than
other -- than
the immigrant or others?

47:38.989 --> 47:42.626 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VIET THANH NGUYEN: I think
immigrants do feel
some of that attachment to
wherever they came

47:42.659 --> 47:47.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from, but they usually made a
choice to go
somewhere, and they have decided
to look forward

47:47.664 --> 47:48.932 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to some extent.

47:48.966 --> 47:52.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But refugees are often compelled
to leave
by violent circumstance.

47:52.436 --> 47:54.705 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're really still attached to
wherever
they came from.

47:54.738 --> 47:58.942 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, that's where I think
refugees oftentimes
have a hard time adjusting, at
least psychologically.

47:58.976 --> 48:03.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They may adjust culturally and
economically,
but, psychologically, half of
them is still

48:03.547 --> 48:05.349 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
somewhere else.

48:05.382 --> 48:08.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, in the first
story in this
new collection, "Black-Eyed
Women," the main

48:08.352 --> 48:13.924 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
character is a woman who's a
Vietnamese American
ghostwriter, right?

48:13.957 --> 48:16.860 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So she's actually there, but not
there, literally.

48:16.894 --> 48:18.662 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
VIET THANH NGUYEN: Right.

48:18.695 --> 48:22.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I wanted to make it sort
of a story
that was about ghosts in many
different ways.

48:22.165 --> 48:25.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She's a ghostwriter, but she's
actually haunted
by a real ghost.

48:25.235 --> 48:27.004 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

48:27.037 --> 48:28.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VIET THANH NGUYEN: And that
ghost is of her
dead brother, who she thought
had died on

48:28.906 --> 48:30.274 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the escape from Vietnam on a
boat.

48:30.307 --> 48:32.542 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then, one night, he comes
knocking on
the door.

48:32.576 --> 48:35.879 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's literally a ghost who swam
thousands
of miles to get to her door.

48:35.913 --> 48:40.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's about the figurative
and the literal
hauntings that so many people
who have escaped

48:40.150 --> 48:42.252 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
through traumatic circumstances
continue to
live with.

48:42.286 --> 48:43.253 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Right.

48:43.287 --> 48:44.721 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But the emphasis is on the real
ghost, right?

48:44.755 --> 48:46.256 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
VIET THANH NGUYEN: Right.

48:46.290 --> 48:51.962 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, real, as in
these people
are alive for your characters?

48:51.995 --> 48:53.363 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
VIET THANH NGUYEN: Yes.

48:53.397 --> 48:55.565 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think, for many people --
many cultures,
ghosts really exist.

48:55.599 --> 48:59.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, literally, Vietnamese
people, for
example, often recount being
visited by people

48:59.836 --> 49:02.773 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who have just died, not to haunt
them, but
to come and say goodbye.

49:02.806 --> 49:06.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: As I read through
the stories
in this book, you have got
characters who

49:06.710 --> 49:09.279 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have lived here in the U.S. for
a long time.

49:09.313 --> 49:11.848 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You have stories set in Vietnam.

49:11.882 --> 49:13.283 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You have Americans going back.

49:13.317 --> 49:15.719 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What are you exploring through
these stories?

49:15.752 --> 49:20.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VIET THANH NGUYEN: I think that,
when I say
Vietnamese to Americans or to
other people,

49:20.424 --> 49:24.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there might be this idea that
there's only
one Vietnamese kind of culture
or one Vietnamese

49:24.161 --> 49:26.063 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
kind of people, and I'm going to
speak for
them.

49:26.096 --> 49:28.398 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But Vietnamese are just like
everybody else.

49:28.432 --> 49:30.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And they're diverse.

49:30.267 --> 49:32.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So this is a collection where I
wanted to
talk about the young and the
old, the straight

49:32.769 --> 49:36.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the gay, the conservative
and the radicals,
the ones who stayed and ones who
went back,

49:36.873 --> 49:40.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to give people a sense of how
heterogeneous
and contradictory these people
are.

49:40.877 --> 49:46.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Are you aware, as
the readers
are aware, of the newness of
this voice in

49:46.616 --> 49:47.584 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
our literature?

49:47.617 --> 49:49.419 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I mean, do you feel that?

49:49.453 --> 49:52.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VIET THANH NGUYEN: I think so,
because, in
order to be a writer, you need
to read a lot

49:52.789 --> 49:54.358 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in the traditions in which you
write.

49:54.391 --> 49:56.193 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

49:56.226 --> 49:57.060 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VIET THANH NGUYEN: So, I have
read a lot of
Vietnamese writing,
Asian-American writing,

49:57.094 --> 49:58.996 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and American writing.

49:59.029 --> 50:02.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the novel is explicitly
designed to provoke
all these different categories
and do things

50:02.566 --> 50:06.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that I don't think has been done
before in
those categories, including in
contemporary

50:06.370 --> 50:08.105 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
American fiction.

50:08.138 --> 50:10.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I want to ask you
about you
and your ghosts, because you
say, I was born

50:10.374 --> 50:12.976 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in Vietnam, but made in America.

50:13.010 --> 50:16.046 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To what extent do you feel
yourself of two
worlds?

50:16.079 --> 50:19.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VIET THANH NGUYEN: Well, when I
was growing
up, I felt myself to be a spy in
my parents'

50:19.616 --> 50:22.285 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
household, because they were
Vietnamese, and
I was being Americanized.

50:22.319 --> 50:26.923 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then, when I went outside, I
was a Vietnamese
spying on Americans.

50:26.957 --> 50:31.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that sense of always being
an observer,
always being a spy has continued
to stay with

50:31.728 --> 50:33.630 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
me.

50:33.663 --> 50:36.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's been influenced by this
refugee past,
the sense of being haunted by
what has impacted

50:36.433 --> 50:39.069 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
my parents and my Vietnamese
community.

50:39.102 --> 50:42.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's been productive, in the
sense that
it has made me into a writer, to
always be

50:42.572 --> 50:45.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
able to see things from the
inside and the
outside, to always be observing,
to always

50:45.842 --> 50:47.177 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
be spying on people.

50:47.210 --> 50:49.212 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's really enormously useful
for a writer.

50:49.246 --> 50:53.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it means I have to allow
myself to not
forget that sense of haunting
